BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Household Finance Corp. -- $150 million of 9% senior notes
due Sept. 1, 1995, priced at 99.80 to yield 9.05%. The
non-callable notes were priced at a spread of 72 basis points
above the Treasury's five-year note. Rated single-A-2 by
Moody's Investors Service Inc. and single-A-plus by Standard
&amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters
led by Salomon Brothers Inc.
   Southern California Edison Co. -- $100 million of 8 1/4%
first and refunding mortgage bonds due Aug. 15, 1993,
reoffered via a group led by Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. at 99.80 to
yield 8.325%. The bonds, which are non-callable, were priced
at 25 basis points above the Treasury's three-year note. The
issue is rated double-A-2 by Moody's and double-A by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Tennessee Housing Development Agency -- $78.6 million of
single-family mortgage revenue bonds, via a Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets group. The bonds, rated single-A by Moody's,
were priced at par. Serial bonds yield from 6.20% in 1992 to
7.40% in 2005. There are term bonds yielding 7 1/2% due in
2010 and 7 5/8% due in 2022.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Chase Mortgage Finance -- $111 million of 9.35% Remic
mortgage securities offered in four classes by Greenwich
Capital Markets Inc. The offering, Series 1990-D, is backed
by whole loans with a weighted average coupon rate of 10.93%
and weighted average remaining term to maturity of 27.5
years.. Prices range from 82.03125 for the accrual class with
an average life of 18.11 years to 100.0625 for the class with
an average life of 3.39 years. The issue is rated double-A-2
by S&amp;P and double-A by Moody's.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   State Bank of New South Wales (Australia) -- 100 million
Australian dollars of 14 1/4% Eurobonds due Sept. 12, 1994,
priced at 101 1/8 for a yield less fees of 14.47% via
Deutsche Bank Capital Markets Ltd. Guaranteed by the
government of New South Wales. Fees 1 3/4.
   Aegon N.V. (Netherlands) -- 100 million guilders of bonds
due Oct. 1, 1997, priced at 101.15 via Rabobank Nederland.
Coupon 10% for first two years and 16 3/4% less the 12-month
Amsterdam interbank offered rate for the final five years.
Investor guaranteed a minimum return of 4 1/2%. Fees 1.
