<HL>
   Broker, Ex-Print Aide
   Must Pay Back Funds
   In Insider-Trade Case
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   MHP
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   A judge ordered a stockbroker and a former printing-plant
employee to pay $66,099 for committing securities fraud by
trading on information from advance copies of Business Week.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission sued former
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. broker Brian Callahan of
Anaheim, Calif., and former print worker William Jackson of
Long Beach, Calif., in January. In May, a jury found that the
men had traded on confidential information.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The SEC charged that Mr. Jackson, who worked at the
Torrance, Calif., printing plant of R.R. Donnelly &amp; Sons Co.,
one of the companies that prints Business Week for
McGraw-Hill Inc., traded on information from the magazine
before it hit the newsstands, and then passed the information
on to Mr. Callahan.
   U.S. District Judge Stephen V. Wilson ordered Mr. Callahan
to repay the $1,148.19 he made, plus $8,000 in commissions he
earned by trading on the information. He was also fined
$27,444.57, three times the amount he was ordered to return
and the maximum allowed under securities laws. Mr. Jackson
was ordered to repay profits of $19,506.99 and was fined
$10,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
