<HL>
   SEC Is Seeking Comment
   On Issues by Foreign Banks
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
BANKS (BNK)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commission voted
to seek comment on a proposal that would make it easier for
foreign banks and insurance companies to offer securities to
U.S. investors.
   The proposal would exempt foreign banks and insurers, as
well as their finance subsidiaries, from the Investment
Company Act, which regulates mutual funds. U.S. banks and
insurance companies already are exempt from the act.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago, the SEC exempted from the Investment
Company Act issues of debt securities and nonvoting preferred
stock by foreign banks and insurers. The proposal would
expand the exemption to include offerings or sales of all
equity securities by foreign banks and insurers.
   Foreign banks and insurers would still be required to file
registration statements and periodic reports under other
securities law. Those filings are far less onerous than the
requirements under the Investment Company Act.
   For practical purposes, however, the rule hasn't prevented
foreign banks and insurance companies from offering their
securities in the U.S. The SEC typically grants them
exemptions from the current rule.
   The agency is expected to approve the proposal after a
60-day comment period.
   The agency also voted to issue an interpretive release
stating that U.S. branches and agencies of foreign banks are
exempt from the Investment Company Act for the limited
purpose of issuing securities in the U.S.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900816-0038
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900816-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Auto Insurer Backs Down
   Under New Jersey Order
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   ITT
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   An insurance group within ITT Corp. edged back from a
confrontation with the state of New Jersey by agreeing to
continue writing auto insurance policies in the state if
necessary to keep the rest of its business there.
   ITT Hartford Insurance Group, which has said its total
premium volume in New Jersey last year was $224.6 million,
was responding to an order by the state insurance
commissioner, Samuel Fortunato, who ordered all ITT Hartford
units to surrender their certificates to sell insurance if
one of those units, Twin City Fire Insurance Co., withdrew
from the state's auto insurance market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Twin City, the only ITT Hartford unit selling auto
insurance in New Jersey, has protested that it would suffer
"severe losses" under the state's new auto-insurance law. The
unit had premium volume of $72.6 million last year, though
that figure includes premiums on homeowner lines as well as
auto coverage.
   The state says Twin City insures about 1% of New Jersey
drivers.
   ITT Hartford said it "will continue to operate within the
letter and spirit of the law." But the company signaled its
dispute with the state isn't over, saying it will seek
"administrative and legal remedies" to Mr. Fortunato's order.
The company has already been in litigation with the state
over the law.
   The insurance commissioner was acting under what state
officials call a "long arm" provision in the law meant to
strengthen the state's position in dealing with insurers who
want to pull out of the auto insurance market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900816-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900816-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Bond Corp. Holdings Ltd.:
   Shareholders of Firm's Unit
   Agree to Purchase Breweries
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   A.BON A.LIO A.BEL
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
</IN>
<LP>
   A settlement for the sale of Alan Bond's Australian
breweries appeared to head off threats by disgruntled U.S.
investors to liquidate the operations. The accord means Mr.
Bond's brewing stake will be diluted by a big new
shareholder-New Zealand brewer Lion Nathan Ltd.
   For months, Bond Corp. Holdings Ltd. has been trying to
sell the breweries to its 58%-owned Bell Resources Ltd. unit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Bell Resources approved that company's
proposal to purchase Bond Corp.'s Australian breweries for a
previously agreed price of A$1.85 billion. Bell Resources has
a longstanding loan to cash-strapped Bond Corp. of A$1.2
billion; it has been turned into a deposit on the breweries.
The sale is part of a corporate overhaul intended to reduce
debt that totals about five billion Australian dollars
(US$4.03 billion).
   Just ahead of the shareholders meeting, Bell Resources
announced a proposal to sell half the breweries to Lion
Nathan, partly in return for a commitment from Lion Nathan to
provide A$300 million to help fund the repurchase of US$510
million in debentures issued to American investors by Bond
Brewing Holdings Ltd., the Bond group's main Australian beer
unit.
</TEXT>
