<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Warner-Lambert Tests Gum
   With No Sugar, No Stick
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WLA WWY
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   MORRIS PLAINS, N.J. -- In a bid to capture a bigger share
of the post-bubble gum set, Warner-Lambert Co. said it is
testing a new sugarless gum that won't stick to dentures.
   The health care and consumer products company said the new
brand, called Cristal, will be available in southern Texas
and Louisiana by mid-September. Cristal was launched in
Canada last year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   With such brands as Trident sugarless gum, Bubblicious
bubble gum and Chiclets sugar-coated gum, Warner-Lambert
already controls about 30% of the $1.8 billion U.S. market
for chewing gum. But that market is slow-growing and
extremely competitive.
   With Cristal, the company is taking aim at consumers 35
years old and over, who have crowns, caps or bridges. The
company estimates that some 30 million Americans wear
dentures, and that at least 80 million have had serious
dental work.
   "Historically, gum chewing declines with age," said Maria
Gagnier, category director for gum at Warner-Lambert. "But as
Baby Boomers age, gum chewing has become more acceptable --
just like Rock &amp; Roll music."
   Warner-Lambert is also hoping Cristal will stick it to top
gum rival Wrigley Co., which lords over the U.S. market with
an estimated 50% share. Wrigley virtually created the U.S.
market for non-stick gums with its Freedent brand, launched
in 1975. The company is now testing a sugarless version of
Freedent, according to a Wrigley spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900816-0027
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900816-0027.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bechtel-Led Group Wins
   High-Speed Rail Franchise
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   J.CIT
</CO>
<IN>
RAILROADS (RAI)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- A consortium led by Bechtel Group Inc.
was awarded a franchise for the development of a $5 billion
high-speed rail system linking Southern California and
Nevada.
   The planned 265-mile system would connect Anaheim, Calif.,
and Las Vegas, Nev., by an elevated magnetized railway
carrying trains that can reach speeds as high as 300 miles an
hour, Bechtel said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Super Speed Maglev Transport system is to be a team
project, coordinated by Bechtel and involving technology from
Transrapid International of Germany, financing by C. Itoh Co.
of Japan, and operations and maintenance services of Amtrak.
   While the system isn't expected to be completed before
1997, Bechtel said the project will eventually create 13,000
to 25,000 permanent jobs in California and 23,000 to 28,000
permanent jobs in Nevada, along with 10,000 temporary
construction jobs.
   Bechtel said it expects the system to attract some five
million round-trip riders a year by the year 2000, drawn by
fares projected at 30% less than commercial airline ticket
prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
