<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   INDUSTRIAL OUTPUT leveled off in July, indicating that the
economy continues to stumble. Factory production slipped 0.1%
and utility output fell 0.4%, but mining posted a 1% gain.
The nation's industrial operating rate fell to 83.4% of
capacity, down from 83.6% in June, which could temper some of
the inflation pressure stemming from higher oil prices.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cutting U.S. dependence on foreign oil by up to 550,000
barrels a day is envisioned under a Bush strategy calling for
voluntary conservation and higher domestic output. The plan
would replace much of the crude the U.S. imported from Iraq
and Kuwait.
   ---
   Stock and bond prices closed slightly higher after Bush
damped early optimism about a possible resolution with Iraq.
The Dow Jones industrials rose half a point to close at
2748.27. The dollar ended mixed.
   ---
   Trump could have a negative net worth of as much as $294
million, newly released documents show. And despite a bank
bailout, the developer could have a $106 million negative
cash flow in the year ending in April.
                                                                                                       

   Atlantic City's casinos posted a collective $4.3 million
loss before extraordinary items, marking the industry's worst
second quarter ever. Trump's three casinos fared much worse
than the other nine houses.
   ---
   Drexel's bankruptcy lawyers were harshly criticized by a
federal judge for the size of their fees. He reduced their
requested payments by 14%.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices soared Wednesday, giving the Nikkei its
third-largest single-day advance. The index jumped 1439.59
points, or 5.4%. But analysts aren't confident that the
market's recent slide is over.
   ---
   Ford's plan to keep $100 million from the pension fund of
a defense unit Ford is selling to Loral is being questioned
by the Pentagon, which says it may lay claim to the money.
                                                                                                       

   Ford is idling two car-assembly plants and extending a
shutdown of a third in the face of sagging sales.
   ---
   Bank of New York's plan to acquire Northeast Bancorp for
$195.6 million was rejected by the Fed, which said the deal
would hurt Bank of New York's capital position.
   ---
   First Executive's customers redeemed $1.2 billion of
insurance policies in the second quarter. The figure, though
declining, indicates that the firm is still under financial
pressure.
   ---
   Sun Microsystems and IBM signed a patent-licensing accord
under which Sun will pay royalties to IBM. The pact comes in
the wake of IBM's tough patent-enforcement policy.
   ---
   Genentech and Abbott Labs settled a two-year-old patent
dispute about Genentech's TPA, removing the last legal cloud
over the heart drug.
   ---
   Tektronix, Zenith Electronics and four other firms were
picked by the Pentagon to work on military uses of
high-definition television.
   ---
   Salomon proposed to offer an equity security that would
allow investors to bet on the price of oil.
   ---
   Columbia S&amp;L estimates the cost of selling its junk-bond
portfolio at $50 million or more, and said its retail deposit
base eroded by nearly $250 million in the past four months.
   ---
   Imperial Oil agreed to sell refining and marketing assets
in Canada's Atlantic Coast provinces, plus some other assets,
in three transactions valued by analysts at about $260
million.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 135,210,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2748.27, up 0.50; transportation 961.68, off 6.02; utilities
205.17, up 0.69.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3386.31, up
7.96.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.16, up 0.21; spot
index 133.06, off 0.44.
   Dollar: 147.65 yen, off 1.13; 1.5660 marks, up 0.0015.
</TEXT>
